    "title": "Toxic Colors: “Some colors are brightly alive, while some mean dead silence.” ",
    "description": "There are few places undisturbed by humans in the world, so we must consider how our existence might affect the Earth.<br/> In my surveys of environmental pollution over the years, every time I set foot on a heavily polluted site, my most intuitive perception was often the sensory stimulation of odors and colors. <br/>In the Tengger Desert in Northwest China, I once saw a sewage lagoon the size of two football fields, with one half being black solid and the other half reddish-brown, viscous fluid, emitting an unusually pungent acid odor. Inside the lagoon were steeped several sand mounds with large patches of auburn blocks. <br/>Compared with odors, colors have the advantage of image expression. The rare strong colors of pollutants, including the contrast of black and white, can be captured to present the indelible marks of human activities on the earth’s surface. <br/>In 2014-2023, I published dozens of image survey reports on China’s environmental problems. Among the environmental pollution incidents covered therein,<br/>15 major ones were investigated under the supervision of the State Council and finally saw the underlying problems solved at the root.",
